untingdonshire, East Yorkshire); or possibly from Weeton, Market Weighton, or Little Weighton (East Yorkshire). The placenames do not all share the same etymology but most of their post-medieval spellings are interchangeable. Most of the placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> or Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some, for example Witton in Warwickshire, derive from Old English <i>wīc</i> ‘dwelling, specialized farmstead’ + <i>tūn</i>, and some others, for example Witton in Norfolk, derive from Old English <i>widu</i> ‘wood’ + <i>tūn</i>. Whitton in Lincolnshire derives from the Old English personal name <i>Hwīta</i> (genitive <i>Hwītan</i>) or Old English <i>hwīt</i> (dative <i>hwītan</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. Witton in Lancashire derives from the Old English personal <i>Witta</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i>.","English: in Devon, this surname is a variant of   Whiddon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitten","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitton   or   Whiting  ."]},{"name":"Whetten","meanings":["English, Scottish, or northern Irish: variant of   Whitton  ."]},{"name":"Whiddon","meanings":["English (Devon): habitational name from any of numerous minor places in Devon named Whiddon. Some are named with Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ or <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’; others with Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> or <i>denu</i> ‘valley’."]},{"name":"Whiton","meanings":["English (Essex): variant of   Whitton  . This surname is now rare in Britain.","History: James Whiton of Hingham, Norfolk, England, came to Plymouth, MA, in 1635."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":72,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Whitton was born in 1310, in England, his father, Johannes Whitton, was 20 and his mother, Miss Johannes Whitton, was 20. He had at least 1 son with mis whitton."},"et":{"1310–":"1310–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1341–Male":"1341–Surnud","1290–1560":"1290–1560","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1315":"13